  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Data Utility Learning"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This notebook introduces **Data Utility Learning**, a method of approximating Data Shapley values by learning to estimate the utility function.\n",
    "\n",
    "The idea is to employ a model to learn the performance of the learning algorithm of interest on unseen data combinations (i.e. subsets of the dataset). The method was originally described in *Wang, Tianhao, Yu Yang, and Ruoxi Jia. [Improving Cooperative Game Theory-Based Data Valuation via Data Utility Learning](https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2107.06336). arXiv, 2022*.\n",
    "\n",
    "<div class=\"alert alert-warning\">\n",
    "**Warning:** Work on Data Utility Learning is preliminary. It remains to be seen when or whether it can be put effectively into application. For this further testing and benchmarking are required.\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Recall the definition of Shapley value $v_u(i)$ for data point $i$:\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "v_u(i) = \\frac{1}{n} \\sum_{S \\subseteq N \\setminus \\{i\\}} \\binom{n-1}{|S|}^{-1} [u(S \\cup \\{i\\}) âˆ’ u(S)] ,\n",
    "\\tag{1}\n",
    "\\label{eq:shapley-def}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "where $N$ is the set of all indices in the training set and $u$ is the utility. To avoid the exponential cost of computing this sum, we set to learn a surrogate model for $u$.\n",
    "\n",
    "In Data Utility Learning, we start by sampling so-called **utility samples** to form a training set  $S_\\text{train}$ for our utility model. Each utility sample is a tuple consisting of a subset of indices $S_j$ in the dataset and its utility $u(S_j)$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\mathcal{S}_\\text{train} = \\{(S_j, v(S_j): j = 1 , ..., m_\\text{train}\\}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $m_\\text{train}$ denotes the *training budget* for the learned utility function.\n",
    "\n",
    "The subsets are then transformed into boolean vectors $\\phi$ in which a $1$ at index $k$ means that the $k$-th sample of the dataset is present in the subset:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$S_j \\mapsto \\phi_j \\in \\{ 0, 1 \\}^{N}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "We fit a regression model $\\tilde{u}$, called **data utility model**, on $\\mathcal{S}_\\text{train}$ and use it to avoid computing the utility for any $S_j \\notin \\mathcal{S}_\\text{train}$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\tilde{u} : \\{ 0, 1 \\}^{N} \\rightarrow \\mathbb{R}. $$\n",
    "\n",
    "The main assumption is that it is much faster to fit and use $\\tilde{u}$ than it is to compute $u$ and that for most $i$, $v_\\tilde{u}(i) \\approx v_u(i)$ in some sense."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Imports\n",
    "\n",
    "We begin by importing the main libraries and setting some defaults.\n",
    "\n",
    "<div class=\"alert alert-info\">\n",
    "**Note:** If you are reading this in the documentation, some boilerplate is left out for your convenience.\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {
    "nbsphinx": "hidden"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%load_ext autoreload"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {
    "nbsphinx": "hidden"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%autoreload\n",
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "\n",
    "import os\n",
    "import random\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "from sklearn.svm import LinearSVC as _LinearSVC\n",
    "from sklearn.datasets import load_iris\n",
    "from sklearn.neural_network import MLPRegressor\n",
    "from sklearn.exceptions import ConvergenceWarning\n",
    "from tqdm.auto import tqdm\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"figure.figsize\"] = (16, 10)\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"font.size\"] = 15\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"xtick.labelsize\"] = 15\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"ytick.labelsize\"] = 15\n",
    "random_state = 24\n",
    "\n",
    "is_CI = os.environ.get(\"CI\")\n",
    "enable_cache = not is_CI\n",
    "\n",
    "if is_CI:\n",
    "    train_size = 5\n",
    "    training_budget_values = np.arange(2, 10, 2)\n",
    "    n_iterations = 1\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    train_size = 15\n",
    "    training_budget_values = np.arange(100, 8000, 250)\n",
    "    n_iterations = 10\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "mlp_kwargs = dict(\n",
    "    hidden_layer_sizes=(20, 10),\n",
    "    activation=\"relu\",\n",
    "    solver=\"adam\",\n",
    "    learning_rate_init=0.001,\n",
    "    batch_size=32,\n",
    "    max_iter=800,\n",
    ")\n",
    "random.seed(random_state)\n",
    "np.random.seed(random_state)\n",
    "\n",
    "from warnings import simplefilter\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "class LinearSVC(_LinearSVC):\n",
    "    def fit(self, X, y, sample_weight=None):\n",
    "        # We inherit to be able to ignore warnings in ray workers\n",
    "        simplefilter(\"ignore\", category=ConvergenceWarning)\n",
    "        return super().fit(X, y)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As is the case with all other Shapley methods, the main entry point is the function [compute_shapley_values()](../pydvl/shapley.rst#pydvl.shapley.compute_shapley_values), which provides a facade to all algorithms in this family. We use it with the usual classes [Dataset](../pydvl/utils/dataset.rst#pydvl.utils.dataset.Dataset) and [Utility](../pydvl/utils/utility.rst#pydvl.utils.utility.Utility). In addition, we must import the core class for learning a utility, [DataUtilityLearning](../pydvl/utils/utility.rst#pydvl.utils.utility.DataUtilityLearning)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from pydvl.utils import (\n",
    "    Dataset,\n",
    "    Utility,\n",
    "    DataUtilityLearning,\n",
    "    top_k_value_accuracy,\n",
    "    available_cpus,\n",
    ")\n",
    "from pydvl.shapley import compute_shapley_values"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "Following the paper, we take 15 samples (10%) from the [Iris dataset](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/datasets/plot_iris_dataset.html) and compute their Data Shapley values by using all the remaining samples as test set for computing the utility, which in this case is accuracy."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dataset = Dataset.from_sklearn(\n",
    "    load_iris(), train_size=0.1, random_state=random_state, stratify=True\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We verify that, as in the paper, if we fit a Support-Vector Classifier to the training data, we obtain an accuracy of around 92%:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Mean accuracy: 92.59%\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = LinearSVC()\n",
    "model.fit(dataset.x_train, dataset.y_train)\n",
    "print(f\"Mean accuracy: {100 * model.score(dataset.x_test, dataset.y_test):0.2f}%\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## Data Shapley\n",
    "\n",
    "We start by defining the utility using the model and computing the exact Data Shapley values by definition $\\ref{eq:shapley-def}$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "utility = Utility(model=model, data=dataset, enable_cache=enable_cache)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "1"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 9,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "df = compute_shapley_values(\n",
    "    u=utility,\n",
    "    mode=\"combinatorial_exact\",\n",
    "    n_jobs=available_cpus(),\n",
    "    progress=True,\n",
    ")\n",
    "df = df.rename(columns={\"data_value\": \"exact\"})"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We now estimate the Data Shapley values using the [DataUtilityLearning](../pydvl/utils/utility.rst#pydvl.utils.utility.DataUtilityLearning) wrapper. For the utility model we do as in the paper and use a fully connected neural network. To train it we use a total of `training_budget` of utility samples. We repeat this for each training budget.\n",
    "\n",
    "**FIXME:** repeat this multiple times in order to better estimate errors."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "application/vnd.jupyter.widget-view+json": {
       "model_id": "a7f55d9c09e0440289f80f919e981587",
       "version_major": 2,
       "version_minor": 0
      },
      "text/plain": [
       "  0%|          | 0/32 [00:00<?, ?it/s]"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "for idx, training_budget in enumerate(training_budget_values):\n",
    "    dul_utility = DataUtilityLearning(\n",
    "        u=utility, training_budget=training_budget, model=MLPRegressor(**mlp_kwargs)\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    dul_df = compute_shapley_values(\n",
    "        u=dul_utility,\n",
    "        mode=\"combinatorial_exact\",\n",
    "        n_jobs=available_cpus(),\n",
    "        progress=False,\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    dul_df = dul_df.rename(columns={\"data_value\": f\"{training_budget}_{idx}\"})\n",
    "    df = pd.concat([df, dul_df], axis=1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next we compute the mean, minimum and maximum absolute error for the different training budget values and look at the results. The plot matches the one in the paper and shows that the method works for estimating the Data Shapley values."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {
    "nbsphinx": "hidden"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "errors = np.zeros((len(training_budget_values), n_iterations), dtype=float)\n",
    "accuracies = np.zeros((len(training_budget_values), n_iterations), dtype=float)\n",
    "\n",
    "top_k = 3\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(len(training_budget_values)):\n",
    "    for j in range(n_iterations):\n",
    "        y_true = df[\"exact\"].values\n",
    "        y_estimated = df[f\"{training_budget_values[i]}_{j}\"].values\n",
    "        errors[i, j] = np.linalg.norm(y_true - y_estimated, ord=2)\n",
    "        accuracies[i, j] = top_k_value_accuracy(y_true, y_estimated, k=top_k)\n",
    "\n",
    "error_from_mean = np.linalg.norm(df[\"exact\"].values - df[\"exact\"].values.mean(), ord=2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "nbsphinx": "hidden"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "ax.plot(\n",
    "    training_budget_values, errors.mean(axis=1), \"dodgerblue\", label=\"Estimated values\"\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.fill_between(\n",
    "    training_budget_values,\n",
    "    errors.min(axis=1),\n",
    "    errors.max(axis=1),\n",
    "    facecolor=\"lightblue\",\n",
    "    alpha=0.5,\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.hlines(\n",
    "    error_from_mean,\n",
    "    training_budget_values.min(),\n",
    "    training_budget_values.max(),\n",
    "    \"indianred\",\n",
    "    label=\"Mean of Exact values\",\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"$m_\\text{train}$\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"$L_2$ Error\")\n",
    "plt.legend()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1600x1000 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us next look at how well the ranking of values resulting from using the surrogate $\\tilde{u}$ matches the true ranking. For this we fix $k=3$ and consider the $k$ samples with the highest value according to $\\tilde{u}$ and $u$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "nbsphinx": "hidden"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "ax.plot(\n",
    "    training_budget_values,\n",
    "    accuracies.mean(axis=1),\n",
    "    \"dodgerblue\",\n",
    "    label=\"Estimated values\",\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.fill_between(\n",
    "    training_budget_values,\n",
    "    accuracies.min(axis=1),\n",
    "    accuracies.max(axis=1),\n",
    "    facecolor=\"lightblue\",\n",
    "    alpha=0.5,\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"$m_\\text{train}$\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"Average Top-3 Accuracy\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1600x1000 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "nbsphinx": "hidden"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally, we  compare the best approximate values obtained and their distance to the true ones\n",
    "(**FIXME:** use boxplot or similar here)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {
    "nbsphinx": "hidden"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "best_training_budget = training_budget_values[errors.mean(axis=1).argmin()]\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(18, 12))\n",
    "df.plot(\n",
    "    y=[\"exact\", f\"{best_training_budget}_{0}\"],\n",
    "    kind=\"bar\",\n",
    "    ax=ax,\n",
    "    color=[\"dodgerblue\", \"indianred\"],\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"Index\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"Data Shapley value\")\n",
    "plt.legend([\"Exact\", \"Estimated\"])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1800x1200 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Evaluation on anomalous data\n",
    "\n",
    "One interesting way to assess the Data Utility Learning approach is to corrupt some of the data and monitor how the valuation score changes. To do this, we will take the sample with the highest score and change its label."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "highest_value_index = df.index[df[\"exact\"].argmax()]\n",
    "y_train_corrupted = dataset.y_train.copy()\n",
    "y_train_corrupted[highest_value_index] = (\n",
    "    y_train_corrupted[highest_value_index] + 1\n",
    ") % 3\n",
    "\n",
    "corrupted_dataset = Dataset(\n",
    "    x_train=dataset.x_train,\n",
    "    y_train=y_train_corrupted,\n",
    "    x_test=dataset.x_test,\n",
    "    y_test=dataset.y_test,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We retrain the model on the new dataset and verify that the accuracy decreases:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "0.8296296296296296"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 17,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = LinearSVC()\n",
    "model.fit(dataset.x_train, y_train_corrupted)\n",
    "print(f\"Mean accuracy: {100 * model.score(dataset.x_test, dataset.y_test):0.2f}%\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally, we recompute the scores of all samples using the exact method and the best training budget previously obtained and then plot the resulting scores. We can see in the figure that both methods assign the lowest value to the sample with the corrupted label."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "utility = Utility(\n",
    "    model=LinearSVC(),\n",
    "    data=corrupted_dataset,\n",
    "    enable_cache=False,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "df_corrupted = compute_shapley_values(\n",
    "    u=utility,\n",
    "    mode=\"combinatorial_exact\",\n",
    "    progress=False,\n",
    ")\n",
    "df_corrupted = df_corrupted.rename(columns={\"data_value\": \"exact\"})\n",
    "\n",
    "dul_utility = DataUtilityLearning(\n",
    "    u=utility, training_budget=best_training_budget, model=MLPRegressor(**mlp_kwargs)\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "dul_df = compute_shapley_values(\n",
    "    u=dul_utility,\n",
    "    mode=\"combinatorial_exact\",\n",
    "    progress=False,\n",
    ")\n",
    "dul_df = dul_df.rename(columns={\"data_value\": \"estimated\"})\n",
    "df_corrupted = pd.concat([df_corrupted, dul_df], axis=1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1600x1000 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "df_corrupted.plot(\n",
    "    y=[\"exact\", \"estimated\"], kind=\"bar\", ax=ax, color=[\"dodgerblue\", \"indianred\"]\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"Index\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"Data Shapley value\")\n",
    "plt.legend([\"Exact\", \"Estimated\"])\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-warning\">\n",
    "As mentioned above, despite the previous results, this work is preliminary and the usefulness of Data Utility Learning remains to be tested in practice.\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "For one, as can be seen in the first figure, the error of the estimated utility doesn't go below the error of true utility mean.\n",
    "This can either be due to the fact that for this dataset all the utility values are close to each other and that's why the mean is a better predictor, or due to the method not learning anything useful apart from the mean.\n"
   ]
  }
 ],
